Khar'Daan is the desert civilization's greatest contradiction: a city built to defeat decay that was itself undone by water. A funerary bureaucracy powered by aquifer engineering, not merely a necropolis. It preserved bodies, identities, contracts, and dynastic legitimacy across generations through the Covenant of Salt and Flow: burial licenses required measured water contributions to public wells, making death a public infrastructure transaction. Architecture in three tiers: upper (ceremonial roads, legal inspection gates, processional), middle (natron halls, resin houses, canopic workshops, inscription foundries), lower (sealed archive vaults stabilized by regulated water pressure and calibrated sluices). The Ninth Meridian Aftershock destabilized the necropolis through doctrinal schism: sluice crews loyal to rival doctrines altered calibration schedules, seal-priests invoked incompatible closure sequences. The Black Reed Breach flooded the archive quarter; the Cartouche Panic saw noble houses break seals to retrieve ancestors, spreading contamination; High Priest Sethnekh refused full evacuation and initiated Perpetual Custody doctrine. Sethnekh's doctrine: dead who served administration in life would serve in death; archives would be defended by bound intellects; sovereign legitimacy held in phylacteric reserve until lawful reunification. This produced oathbound revenant cohorts, annalist wraiths, sentinel constructs keyed to obsolete warrants, and phylactery-linked command entities. The Dread Pharaoh is less a single person than a composite rulership-state assembled from dynastic remains, legal titles, and bound command glyphs — the Crown Without Breath — commanding through three fused artifacts: Solar Mask of Mandate, Sealed Tide Cartouche, and Night Ledger Core. Khar'Daan's administrative innovations survive in Mafdet's Quarantine Ledger, which derives its four-tier hazard classification directly from Khar'Daan's containment-class system.

